## Detecting Environment
### Default Detection

By default, Vapor will first check for an env cli argument, and then default to "local" if there isn't one present.  _NOTE: Detection should default to production, not local, in release builds but I was unable to figure out how to detect release builds via SPM building._
##### Specifying an environment at runtime:

``` bash
./.build/debug/App --env=test
```
### Overriding Detection

To override detection, can set an environment detection handler on Application:

``` swift
let app = Application()
app.detectEnvironmentHandler = { env in
   #if os(Linux)
      if env == "test" {
         return .Test
      } else {
         return .Production
      }
   #else
      return .Development
   #endif
}
```
## Querying Environment
### Simple

For a simple comparison, you can use the environment var on Application an do:

``` swift
if app.environment == .Production {
   print("In Production")
}
```
### Advanced

For more advanced querying, Application has an inEnvironment() method which can take any number of arguments and will return true if any of them match:

``` swift
if app.inEnvironment(.Production, .Test) {
   print("In Production or Test")
} else {
   print("Somewhere else: \(app.environment)")
}
```
